Synchronous Programming vs Asynchronous Programming are two different ways to write code that perform tasks sequentially or non-sequentially in JavaScript.

**Syncroneous (Blocking) Programming:**
In synchronous programming, your program waits for a task to complete before moving on to the next one. This is also called "blocking". When you call an asynchronous function and it returns a Promise object, it means that there's something outside of its control waiting to be resolved or rejected. For example, making HTTP requests (fetch), database calls(node-postgres), file system operations etc are all examples where synchronous programming is used because the code will not move on until the task has been completed.

Example:
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const data = 'This is a string that I want to read from a file';
fs.readFile('./example.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
  if(err) throw err;
  console.log(`Successfully Read Data: ${data}`);
});
```
**Asynchronous Programming:**
In asynchronous programming, your program will continue running while waiting for a task to complete. This is also called "non-blocking". An async function always returns Promise object and it doesn't block the code execution in any other parts of application. Promises are like an empty inbox; when you put something into that box (resolvePromise()), others can see it only after the promise has been fulfilled.
Example:
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
async function readDataAsync() {
  let data;
  try {
    data = await new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      fs.readFile('./example.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
        if(err) {
          reject('Error reading file');
        } else {
          resolve(data);
        }
      });
    });
     console.log(`Successfully Read Data: ${data}`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to read data from the file", error);
  }
}
readDataAsync();
```
In asynchronous programming, we use `async` function that returns a Promise and this function will run in parallel with other tasks instead of blocking them.

